3.1.1 4.0.0 <- 3.x.x
--------------------

Version 4.0 introduces major improvements to keyword configuration and
project management.  Your existing GTD data will continue to work, but
you'll need to update your configuration and optionally migrate to take
full advantage of new features.

   • Required: Configuration changes

     *1.  Update keyword configuration*

     *OLD way (version 3.x):*
          ;; Individual keyword variables (no longer used)
          (setq org-gtd-next "NEXT")
          (setq org-gtd-todo "TODO")
          (setq org-gtd-wait "WAIT")
          (setq org-gtd-canceled "CNCL")

     *NEW way (version 4.0):*
          ;; First, configure org-mode's global TODO keywords
          ;; All your GTD keywords must be in the same sequence
          (setq org-todo-keywords
                '((sequence "TODO" "NEXT" "WAIT" "|" "DONE" "CNCL")))

          ;; Then map GTD semantic states to your keywords
          ;; Use setopt (Emacs 29+) for automatic validation, or setq for older versions
          (setopt org-gtd-keyword-mapping
                  '((todo . "TODO")      ;; tasks not ready to be acted upon
                    (next . "NEXT")      ;; tasks ready to act on immediately
                    (wait . "WAIT")      ;; tasks blocked or delegated
                    (done . "DONE")      ;; tasks successfully completed
                    (canceled . "CNCL"))) ;; tasks that won't be completed

     Steps:
       1. Remove old keyword variables (‘org-gtd-next’, ‘org-gtd-todo’,
          ‘org-gtd-wait’, ‘org-gtd-canceled’ and their ‘-suffix’
          variants) from your configuration
       2. Remove any ‘#+TODO:’ lines from your GTD org files (inbox.org,
          org-gtd-tasks.org, etc.)
       3. Add the global keyword configuration to your Emacs init file
       4. Ensure all GTD keywords appear in the *same sequence* in
          ‘org-todo-keywords’

   • Required: Data migration

     Version 4.0 changes how projects work internally.  *The old
     TRIGGER-based system no longer functions* - v4 uses dependency
     properties instead.  You MUST run the migration for your existing
     projects to continue working.

     *Run the migration command:*

          M-x org-gtd-upgrade-v3-to-v4

     *Make a backup first!*  The migration modifies your GTD files.

     *What the migration does:*

     The migration performs three steps automatically:

       1. *Adds ORG_GTD properties* to identify items:
             • Adds ‘ORG_GTD="Projects"’ to project headings
             • Adds ‘ORG_GTD="Actions"’ to project tasks

       2. *Migrates delegated items* to use their own type:
             • Changes ‘ORG_GTD’ from "Actions" to "Delegated" for items
               with ‘DELEGATED_TO’ property
             • This separates delegated items from regular single
               actions

       3. *Converts projects to dependency-based system*:
             • Adds ‘ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON’ and ‘ORG_GTD_BLOCKS’ properties
               to create sequential task chains
             • Adds ‘ORG_GTD_FIRST_TASKS’ property to project headings
             • Updates task states (NEXT/TODO) based on the new
               dependency graph

     *After migration:*

        • Your projects continue to work sequentially (task 1 → task 2 →
          task 3)
        • The sequential behavior is now implemented via dependency
          properties instead of TRIGGER
        • You can now customize dependencies for individual projects if
          you want parallel tasks
        • Safe to run multiple times if needed

   • Why these changes?

     *Keyword configuration:*
        • Simpler: One mapping structure instead of multiple variables
        • More reliable: Global configuration avoids file-level
          conflicts
        • Better validation: Org GTD checks your configuration and
          provides helpful errors
        • Future-proof: Easier to extend with new keyword types

     *Property-based system:*
        • More robust: Properties work reliably across different
          org-mode features
        • More flexible: Enables features like multi-project tasks
        • Better performance: Faster queries using org-ql

   • org-gtd-mode has a new purpose

     The ‘org-gtd-mode’ minor mode has been redesigned in version 4.0.
     It no longer wraps org-agenda commands—instead, it provides useful
     mode-line feedback.

     *What it does now:*
        • Displays inbox count in your mode-line (e.g., ‘GTD[5]’)
        • Includes items from both main inbox and additional inbox files
        • Refreshes periodically to catch external file changes

     *To enable:*
          (org-gtd-mode 1)

     *Note*: You still need to configure ‘org-agenda-files’ and
     ‘org-edna’ separately:
          (setq org-agenda-files (list org-gtd-directory))
          (org-edna-mode 1)


