5.2.4 Organizing an item into the system
----------------------------------------

When you are done clarifying, call ‘M-x org-gtd-organize’ (or hit your
keybinding for it, see *note Recommended key bindings::).  This will
open a transient menu to let you choose how Org GTD should categorize
this item.

   Organizing is broken up into three steps:
   • Choosing a task type (see *note Understanding GTD Item Types::)
   • Applying hooks to add additional relevant information (see *note
     Hooks Framework Reference::)
   • Refiling to the appropriate area (see *note Refiling: Refiling to
     the appropriate area. below)

   *See also*: *note Commands Reference:: for the ‘org-gtd-organize’
command and all organization-related commands.

   • Refiling to the appropriate area

        • Understanding Refiling in V4

          In org-gtd v4, refiling is *optional organizational
          preference*, not a structural requirement.  Items can exist
          anywhere in your ‘org-agenda-files’.

          By default, org-gtd uses ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ properties to mark
          refile target headings.  These can be at *any level* in *any
          file* in ‘org-agenda-files’.

        • Refile Target System

          Org-gtd *merges* your ‘org-refile-targets’ configuration with
          its own ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ property-based targets:

            1. Your configured ‘org-refile-targets’ appear first
            2. Org-gtd's ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ targets appear after

          This means you can use both org-mode's standard refile
          configuration AND org-gtd's property-based system together.

          Org-gtd finds refile targets by searching for ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’
          property:

               * Projects         <-- Can be anywhere, any level
               :PROPERTIES:
               :ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects
               :END:

               ** Work/
               *** Development Projects   <-- Also a valid refile target!
               :PROPERTIES:
               :ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects
               :END:

          When you organize an item as a Project, org-gtd finds *all*
          headings with ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects’ (plus any targets
          from your ‘org-refile-targets’).

             • Choosing Between Multiple Targets

               By default (‘org-gtd-refile-to-any-target’ is ‘t’),
               org-gtd automatically refiles to the first target found
               without prompting.  If you have multiple refile targets
               and want to choose between them:

                    (setq org-gtd-refile-to-any-target nil)

               With this setting, org-gtd will always prompt you to
               select from available targets.

        • Creating New Refile Targets

          To create a new refile target, add ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ property
          to any heading:

          For Projects:
               * My Projects
               :PROPERTIES:
               :ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects
               :END:

          For other types, use the appropriate template constant value:
             • Projects: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects’
             • Actions: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Actions’
             • Calendar: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Calendar’
             • Tickler: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Tickler’
             • Someday: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Someday’
             • Habits: ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Habits’

          If no refile target exists when organizing, org-gtd
          automatically creates one in your default GTD file.

        • Using Your Own Refile Targets

          If you have existing ‘org-refile-targets’ configuration,
          org-gtd automatically merges your targets with its own:

               ;; Your refile configuration is respected and merged
               (setq org-refile-targets '(("~/org/notes.org" :maxlevel . 2)
                                          ("~/org/work.org" :maxlevel . 3)))

          Your targets appear *first* in the refile completion list,
          followed by org-gtd's ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ targets.  Files inside
          ‘org-gtd-directory’ are filtered by the ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’
          property; files outside are available as-is.

        • Migration from V3

          V3 required this structure:
               * Projects      <-- MUST be level 1
               :PROPERTIES:
               :ORG_GTD: Projects    <-- Dual-purpose property
               :END:

          V4 is flexible:
               * Projects      <-- Can be anywhere, any level
               :PROPERTIES:
               :ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects    <-- Marks refile target
               :END:

          The upgrade script (‘org-gtd-upgrade-v3-to-v4’) automatically
          renames ‘ORG_GTD’ → ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ on your old category
          headings.


