5.3.8 Someday/Maybe [y]
-----------------------

*What it is*: Ideas or possibilities with no specific timeframe - things
you might do eventually but have no commitment to.

   *When to use it*: For ideas you want to keep but aren't ready to
commit time or energy to, and don't need a specific review date.

   *Examples*:
   • Learn Spanish (someday)
   • Write a book (maybe)
   • Build a woodworking shop (no timeline)
   • Take photography class (when life permits)

   *What org-gtd does*:
   • Sets ‘ORG_GTD: Someday’ property (no timestamp)
   • Refiles to a someday/maybe category
   • Stays out of active views until you explicitly review it

   *How to review*: Use ‘org-gtd-reflect-someday-maybe’ to periodically
review all someday items and decide if any are ready to become active
projects or actions.

   *Key difference from Tickler*: Someday items have NO review date.
They don't appear in your agenda automatically.  You choose when to
review them (typically during weekly/monthly reviews).

   *GTD principle*: Someday/maybe items acknowledge possibilities
without cluttering your active system.  They're safe to ignore until
you're ready.

   *State Preservation*: When you move an item TO someday, org-gtd
automatically saves its current state:
   • ‘ORG_GTD’ value → saved to ‘PREVIOUS_ORG_GTD’
   • TODO keyword → saved to ‘PREVIOUS_TODO’
   • Type-specific properties (e.g., ‘DELEGATED_TO’, ‘SCHEDULED’) →
     saved to ‘PREVIOUS_*’ versions

   This means a delegated action moved to someday will remember who it
was delegated to, and a calendar item will remember its original date.

   *Reactivating Someday Items*: When you're ready to work on a someday
item again, use ‘M-x org-gtd-reactivate’.  For non-project items, you'll
be prompted to confirm or update each preserved property (e.g.,
"Delegated to [Jane Smith]: ").  This lets you adjust for the time that
has passed while keeping your original planning work.


