5.4.7 Common Dependency Patterns (Visual Reference)
---------------------------------------------------

Here's what different patterns look like in graph view:

   • Sequential Chain (A → B → C)

          [A - NEXT]
              ↓
          [B - TODO]
              ↓
          [C - TODO]

     *When to use*: Order matters, each task depends on the previous.

     *How to build*: ‘a r’ for A, select A, ‘a s’ for B (check A),
     select B, ‘a s’ for C (check B).

     *Example*: Review blueprints → Order windows → Schedule carpenter

   • Parallel Independent (A, B, C all start together)

          [A - NEXT]  [B - NEXT]  [C - NEXT]

     *When to use*: Tasks are completely independent, all can start
     immediately.

     *How to build*: From project heading, ‘a r’ for each task.

     *Example*: Research destinations, Check budget, Ask for time off
     (vacation planning)

   • Fan-out (A → B, A → C, A → D)

                [A - NEXT]
               /    |    \
              ↓     ↓     ↓
          [B-TODO][C-TODO][D-TODO]

     *When to use*: Initial work enables multiple independent paths.

     *How to build*: ‘a r’ for A, select A, then ‘a s’ three times (B,
     C, D - each checking only A).

     *Example*: Get project approval → (Design UI, Write backend API,
     Setup infrastructure)

   • Fan-in / Convergence (A → C, B → C)

          [A - NEXT]  [B - NEXT]
                \        /
                 ↓      ↓
                [C - TODO]

     *When to use*: Final task needs all previous work completed.

     *How to build*: ‘a r’ for A and B.  Select A, ‘a s’ for C, then
     check BOTH A and B in the checkbox menu.

     *Example*: (Write code, Write tests) → Merge to main

   • Diamond (A → B → D, A → C → D)

              [A - NEXT]
               /      \
              ↓        ↓
          [B-TODO] [C-TODO]
              \      /
               ↓    ↓
             [D-TODO]

     *When to use*: Work splits, proceeds in parallel, then combines.

     *How to build*:
       1. ‘a r’ for A
       2. Select A, ‘a s’ for B (check A)
       3. Select A again, ‘a s’ for C (check A)
       4. Select B, ‘a s’ for D, then check BOTH B and C

     *Example*: Research → (Write content, Design graphics) → Publish
     article


