6.2.6 Custom View Commands
--------------------------

   • ‘org-gtd-view-show’

     **What it is:** Create custom GTD agenda views using a declarative
     language instead of learning org-ql or org-agenda internals.

     **Why you'd use it:** The built-in views (engage,
     review-stuck-projects, etc.)  cover common needs, but you have
     unique workflows.  Maybe you only want to see work-related NEXT
     actions, or projects in a specific area, or items tagged "urgent".
     This lets you create exactly the view you need.

     **Who needs it:** Users who want views tailored to their specific
     workflow beyond the built-in commands.

     **Your first custom view (5 minutes):**

     Let's create a view showing only your NEXT actions (no calendar, no
     agenda).

       1. Add this to your config file:
               (defun my-next-actions ()
                 "Show all NEXT actions in a simple list."
                 (interactive)
                 (org-gtd-view-show
                  '((name . "All NEXT Actions")
                    (type . next-action))))

       2. Save and reload your config (‘M-x eval-buffer’ or restart
          Emacs)

       3. Run it:
               M-x my-next-actions

     You'll see all your NEXT actions in one list.  That's it—you've
     created a custom view!

     **Understanding how views work:**

     Think of views like filtered searches.  You tell org-gtd what to
     show, and it finds matching items.

     The built-in ‘org-gtd-engage’ command?  It uses ‘org-gtd-view-show’
     internally.  ‘org-gtd-reflect-stuck-projects’?  Same thing.  You're
     now using the same tool the package uses to create its own views.

     View specs are simple: give it a ‘name’ and add filters.  Filters
     are pairs like ‘(filter-type . value)’.  Multiple filters combine
     with AND logic—all must match.

          ;; Simple view spec
          '((name . "Delegated Items")
            (type . delegated))

     The most common filter is ‘type’, which matches GTD item types:
     ‘project’, ‘next-action’, ‘calendar’, ‘delegated’, ‘tickler’,
     ‘someday’, ‘habit’, ‘stuck-project’, ‘completed-project’.

     **Tutorial: Common custom views**

     *Show only work-related NEXT actions:*

          (defun my-work-next-actions ()
            "Show NEXT actions for work projects only."
            (interactive)
            (org-gtd-view-show
             '((name . "Work NEXT Actions")
               (type . next-action)
               (area-of-focus . "Work"))))

     Two filters: must be a next-action AND must be in Work area.

     *Show projects that are stuck:*

          (defun my-stuck-projects ()
            "Show projects with no NEXT actions."
            (interactive)
            (org-gtd-view-show
             '((name . "Stuck Projects")
               (type . stuck-project))))

     One filter: type must be stuck-project (built-in type that checks
     for stuck state).

     *Show delegated items due today:*

          (defun my-delegated-today ()
            "Show delegated items with check-ins due today."
            (interactive)
            (org-gtd-view-show
             '((name . "Delegated Check-ins Today")
               (type . delegated)
               (when . today))))

     The ‘when’ filter uses semantic time: ‘today’, ‘past’, or ‘future’.
     It automatically knows that for delegated items, "when" means the
     ‘ORG_GTD_TIMESTAMP’ property.

     *Show multiple related views together:*

          (defun my-morning-review ()
            "Show morning planning views: NEXT actions and calendar."
            (interactive)
            (org-gtd-view-show
             '(((name . "Today's NEXT Actions")
                (type . next-action))
               ((name . "Delegated Items to Follow Up")
                (type . delegated)
                (when . today)))))

     This shows TWO views in one agenda: NEXT actions first, then
     delegated items due today.

     **Common patterns:**

     *Filter by type (most common):*
          (type . project)          ; All projects
          (type . next-action)      ; Single actions (with NEXT keyword)
          (type . delegated)        ; Delegated items (with WAIT keyword)
          (type . calendar)         ; Calendar items
          (type . tickler)          ; Tickler items (time-based reminders)
          (type . someday)          ; Someday/maybe items
          (type . habit)            ; Habits
          (type . stuck-project)    ; Projects needing attention
          (type . completed-project) ; Projects ready to archive

     *Filter by semantic time (‘when’):*
          (when . today)            ; Items due today
          (when . past)             ; Missed items
          (when . future)           ; Upcoming items

     The ‘when’ filter automatically uses the right timestamp property
     for each type:
        • For ‘delegated’ and ‘calendar’: checks ‘ORG_GTD_TIMESTAMP’
        • For ‘tickler’: checks the tickler review date

     *Filter by area of focus:*
          (area-of-focus . "Work")

     *Combine multiple filters (AND logic):*
          '((name . "Overdue Work Projects")
            (type . project)
            (area-of-focus . "Work")
            (deadline . past))
          ;; Shows: Projects AND Work area AND overdue

     **When to create custom views:**

     Create a custom view when you find yourself:
        • Repeatedly filtering the engage view manually
        • Wanting to see specific combinations org-gtd doesn't provide
        • Needing views for specific contexts (home office, traveling,
          morning routine)
        • Organizing weekly reviews around specific categories

     Don't create views for one-time queries—just use the built-in views
     and navigate.  Create views for repeated patterns in your workflow.

     **Binding to keys:**

     Once you've created a view you use often, bind it to a key:

          ;; Vanilla Emacs
          (global-set-key (kbd "C-c d w") 'my-work-next-actions)

          ;; Doom Emacs (in config.el)
          (map! :leader
                (:prefix "d"
                 :desc "Work NEXT actions" "w" #'my-work-next-actions))

          ;; Spacemacs (in user-config)
          (spacemacs/set-leader-keys "od w" 'my-work-next-actions)

     **Complete filter reference:**

     For the full list of available filters and their syntax, see *note
     View DSL Reference: View DSL Filter Reference.

     Common filters include:
     ‘type’
          project, next-action, delegated, calendar, tickler, someday,
          habit, stuck-project, completed-project, stuck-delegated,
          stuck-calendar, stuck-tickler, stuck-habit
     ‘when’
          Semantic time filter (today, past, future) - automatically
          uses correct property per type
     ‘area-of-focus’
          Specific area/category
     ‘deadline’, ‘scheduled’
          Org timestamp filters (past, future, today)
     ‘tags’
          Match specific tags

     **Command reference:**

     *Function signature:*
          (org-gtd-view-show VIEW-SPEC-OR-SPECS)

     *Arguments:*
     ‘VIEW-SPEC-OR-SPECS’
          Either a single view specification (alist) or list of view
          specifications

     *View specification structure:*
          ;; Simple view - filters are top-level
          '((name . "View Name")
            (type . delegated)
            (when . past))

     *Multiple views:*
          '(((name . "View 1")
             (type . next-action))
            ((name . "View 2")
             (type . stuck-project)))

     *Returns:* Opens org-agenda buffer with the specified view

     *Example:*
          ;; Single view
          (org-gtd-view-show
           '((name . "Active Projects")
             (type . project)))

          ;; Multiple views
          (org-gtd-view-show
           '(((name . "NEXT Actions")
              (type . next-action))
             ((name . "Stuck Projects")
              (type . stuck-project))))


