6.5.14 Simplified Multi-Block Views
-----------------------------------

Creating multi-block views usually requires verbose ‘blocks’ syntax.
The View DSL offers a simpler alternative: just list the types you want
to see.

   *For:* Users who want quick multi-block views without boilerplate.

   • The Problem: Verbose Block Definitions

     A typical area-of-focus review view requires this:

          ;; Verbose: every block needs explicit configuration
          '((name . "Health Review")
            (blocks . (((name . "Projects")
                        (type . project)
                        (area-of-focus . "Health"))
                       ((name . "Next Actions")
                        (type . next-action)
                        (area-of-focus . "Health"))
                       ((name . "Calendar")
                        (type . calendar)
                        (area-of-focus . "Health")
                        (when . today)))))

     Notice the repetition: ‘area-of-focus’ appears in every block, and
     you had to remember that ‘calendar’ needs ‘(when . today)’.

   • The Solution: Implicit Blocks

     The same view, simplified:

          ;; Concise: types expand automatically with smart defaults
          '((name . "Health Review")
            (area-of-focus . "Health")
            (type . project)
            (type . next-action)
            (type . calendar))

     When you list multiple ‘type’ keys at the top level, org-gtd
     automatically:
       1. Creates a block for each type
       2. Inherits top-level filters (‘area-of-focus’) to all blocks
       3. Applies smart defaults (e.g., ‘calendar’ gets ‘(when .
          today)’)

   • Try It Now

     Evaluate this (select and run ‘M-x eval-region’):

          (org-gtd-view-show
           '((name . "Quick Dashboard")
             (type . next-action)
             (type . delegated)
             (type . tickler)))

     You get three sections:
        • "Next Actions" - all your NEXT tasks
        • "Delegated" - items due today (smart default: ‘when . today’)
        • "Tickler" - reminders due today (smart default: ‘when .
          today’)

     No ‘blocks’ syntax.  No ‘when’ filters.  org-gtd inferred them.

   • Smart Type Defaults

     Time-sensitive types automatically filter to "today":

     Type              Default ‘when’   Default Name
     ------------------------------------------------------------------
     ‘calendar’        ‘today’          "Calendar"
     ‘delegated’       ‘today’          "Delegated"
     ‘tickler’         ‘today’          "Tickler"
     ‘habit’           --               "Habits"
     ‘next-action’     --               "Next Actions"
     ‘project’         --               "Projects"
     ‘someday’         --               "Someday/Maybe"
     ‘stuck-project’   --               "Projects (Needs Attention)"

     *Why these defaults?*  For calendar, delegated, and tickler items,
     you usually want to see what's relevant _today_.  For other types,
     you want to see everything.

   • Top-Level Inheritance

     Filters at the top level apply to _all_ blocks:

          '((name . "Work Focus")
            (area-of-focus . "Work")  ;; Applied to all blocks
            (type . project)
            (type . next-action)
            (type . delegated))

     This shows only Work-related items across all three sections.

   • The Four-Tier Precedence Model

     When org-gtd expands implicit blocks, it applies settings in this
     order (highest priority first):

       1. *Block-explicit* -- If you use explicit ‘blocks’ syntax and
          set a value, it wins
       2. *Top-level* -- Filters at the view's top level inherit to all
          blocks
       3. *Type smart default* -- Built-in defaults for that type (e.g.,
          ‘calendar’ → ‘when . today’)
       4. *Global defaults* -- Package defaults like
          ‘org-gtd-prefix-width’

     *Example*: Override a smart default:

          ;; Show ALL calendar items, not just today
          '((name . "All Calendar")
            (when . future)  ;; Top-level overrides type default
            (type . calendar))

     *Example*: Mix explicit and implicit:

          '((name . "Mixed View")
            (area-of-focus . "Work")
            (type . next-action)  ;; Gets "Next Actions" name, Work filter
            (type . delegated))   ;; Gets "Delegated" name, Work filter, when=today

   • When to Use Explicit Blocks

     Use explicit ‘blocks’ syntax when you need:
        • Custom block names (implicit blocks use default names)
        • Different filters per block (beyond inheritance)
        • Non-standard block types like ‘calendar-day’ or ‘todo’

     *Example*: Custom names require explicit blocks:

          '((name . "My Dashboard")
            (blocks . (((name . "Today's Schedule")  ;; Custom name
                        (block-type . calendar-day))
                       ((name . "Ready to Work On")  ;; Custom name
                        (type . next-action)))))

   • Quick Reference

     Goal                        Use
     ---------------------------------------------------------
     Simple multi-section view   Multiple ‘(type . X)’ keys
     Custom block names          Explicit ‘blocks’
     Filter all blocks           Top-level filter
     Override smart default      Top-level filter
     Mix native + query blocks   Explicit ‘blocks’


